<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>If you &quot;earned&quot; money, for sake of this argument you can spend them all to the last red cent. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
No, you can't.  Unless it's ALL just a great big hoax!  Let's say for the sake or argument that I am &quot;paid&quot; $50 per hour.  A good wage.  But whoa...here comes taxes and such.  6.2% for SS, so now I'm earning $46.90.  Now here comes Medicare at 1.45% (of 50) and now I'm earning $46.175.  Federal Taxes come in at 19.47%, so that's $36.44 / hour I'm earning.  Look out!  It's state income taxes next at 6.39% (in California) and I'm bringing home $33.245/hour now.  Fortunately, there is a thing called defered compensation where I can hide some of the money away to be taxed at a LATER date, but it can earn some interest untaxed in the meanwhile.  So of my $50/hour, in a two week cycle, with $500 off the top for defered comp and the rest paid to me AFTER TAXES...<br>
$4,000 - $500 = $3,500<br>
$3,500 - (3500*.062) - (3500*.0145) - (3500*.1947) - (3500*.0639) = $2,327.15 on the paycheck every two weeks.  GRANTED, the $500 is there two, but you cannot use it.  Take home wage is $29.09 (as compared to be &quot;paid&quot; $50)<br>
<br>
Sounds like lots of money, right?  In The area I live, It's barely enough to own a house WITH a partner earning a minimum of $50,000 themselves.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Have you read anything in this thread at all? Success isnt the issue in this thread, the issue is ability of large capital to sustain itself and &quot;reproduce&quot; and &quot;grow&quot; (becoming a life form in itself).<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The only way a was able to afford a house in my market was the fact that my mother and fatehr scrimped and saved and acquired a good nest egg.  I followed similar steps and will hopefully be able to leave my children more than what I was left.  I hope they can do the same.  And so on and so on and so on.  Eventually, yes, the &quot;dream&quot; is to make it so that no one in my family ever HAS to work.  It &quot;could&quot; happen this generation, but not freaking likely and I will just continue to buy 5 $1 chances on the lottery when it gets above $50M like the rest of the world.  I am not ignorant to the fact that I have about the same chance of making the money work out in that manner.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I still dont get how Paris Hilton is supporting ANYONE.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
&lt;sigh&gt;  I will not try and argue that Paris isn't worthless.  CLEARLY, she is.  I do applaud her for taking her life by the reins and RUNNING with it.  If I was her, I would.  Wouldn't you?<br>
<br>
But let's face it: Paris employs an arseload of folks in the process.  She probably employs 5 times more people than your average heiress because she goes on the &quot;road&quot; so often.  She is using her family's fortune, yes, but at this point in the game, she's almost certainly breaking even.  She does work pretty darn hard if you stop and think about it.  I wouldn't wanna have to be that avilable all the time.  Would you?  My God!  Sometimes my friends get on my freakin' nerves with planning planning planning for weekends!  I think all of us would like to be able to spend 1 or 2 days per month on a drunken binge or stoend to the bejezzuzz or meditating in a treetop or whatever.<br>
<br>
But agreed: She IS worthless!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>What exactly do you know about socialism and please explain to me in your own words how ECONOMICAL SYSTEM of socialism would encourage corruption<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
In socialism, everyone is moving forward &quot;together&quot; at reasonably the same rate.  Right?  We all have access to the same medical, right?  The same education, right?  The same liesure activities, right?  The same rights to pursue life and liberty and happiness, right (because socialists believe in those ideas too!)?  Surrrrrrrrre.<br>
<br>
Two people from the same family (heck, paternal twins) of very different natural abilities are offered the same education.  One excels tremendously but comes up against the wall of 'normalcy'  To make sure that everyone stays on reasonably the same course, you keep this particularly exceptional person from ever being free to pursue the sky.  But wait...there's a few people out there (HUMAN NATURE) that realize this persons potential.  They harness them in service of 'the people' and milk their talents mercilessly to their own benefit.  The talented person is exploited, a few people benefit, and 'the people' are 'better off'.  You better beleive that folks will focus more attention on keeping the talented twin healthier.  Remember: Serving the greater good.<br>
<br>
Socialism is a GREAT CONCEPT, but in practice, it does not work.  I agree that there MUST be certain basic levels of everything we need to ensure there is a level of human dignity.  Not that you stated such a lofty goal, but that IS the goal, right?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>&quot;well there was corruption in russia, that musta been socialism&quot; dont really fly. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
There wasn't socialism in Russia to fail by corruption, so I'm not sure what exactly you mean.  There was Communism in the Soviet Union, yes.  Socialism in Russia though?  Never.  Just ask the pensioners throughout that country what their lives are like right now.  It's no secret why &quot;strong-man&quot; politics work there.<br>
<br>
Communism or any other one party (or two...?) system obviously doesn't work.  The possibility of graft and corruption are always too high.  A purely socialist country would still be riddled with people that had &quot;extra access&quot; to certain things.  I mean COME ONE!  If only biologists and geologists and the like had access to the wilderness ranges since they are the only ones doing something &quot;meaningful&quot; there and the cost to have it available to everyone was too high and (breathes in again) thus ONLY those folks could go...What the heck kinda place would it be?  You'd have the biologist trading time with the bridge engineer trading time with the neurosurgeon trading time with the lawyer trading time with...<br>
<br>
The systems of entitlement would continue with a different currency, that is all.<br>
<br>
I'll admit that I live in a bourgiose dreamworld where hard work and education and wise investment can pay off in the long run.  But your bong must definitely be WAY bigger than mine to think that pure socialism is the answer.<br>
